Intel=E2=80=99s Modular Vision
----------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-04-09/intel-u=
nveils-new-ai-accelerator-chip-in-bid-to-gain-on-nvidia ) :

Intel Corp. is rolling out a new version of its artificial intelligence chi=
p, aiming to challenge Nvidia Corp. in one of the fastest-growing parts of =
the semiconductor industry. The updated processor, called Gaudi 3, will be =
widely available in the third quarter, Intel said at a company event Tuesda=
y. The chip is designed to boost performance in two key areas: helping trai=
n AI systems =E2=80=94 a process that involves bombarding them with data =
=E2=80=94 and running the finished software=E2=80=A6

Gelsinger declined to give pricing but said that his chips would be =E2=80=
=9Ca lot below=E2=80=9D the cost of Nvidia=E2=80=99s current and future chi=
ps. They=E2=80=99ll provide an =E2=80=9Cextremely good=E2=80=9D total cost =
of ownership, he said. Challenging Nvidia won=E2=80=99t be easy. The runawa=
y success of that company=E2=80=99s H100 accelerator helped more than doubl=
e revenue and sent its market valuation over $2 trillion. And now Nvidia is=
 looking to build on its lead with a just-announced chip platform called Bl=
ackwell. Systems based on that product will be available later this year, t=
he company said in March.

According to Intel=E2=80=99s assessment, Gaudi 3 will be faster and more po=
wer-efficient than the H100. It will train certain types of AI models 1.7 t=
imes more quickly and be 1.5 times better at running the software, the chip=
maker claims. The product will be roughly equal with Nvidia=E2=80=99s newer=
 H200, Intel said, performing slightly better in some areas and a bit behin=
d in others.

I have no idea if that last paragraph is true; every graph in Intel=E2=80=
=99s keynote at Intel Vision 2024 ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DQB7Fo=
Ipx8os ) included this note telling viewers to visit www.intel.com/performa=
nceindex ( https://www.intel.com/performanceindex ) to find out details of =
the benchmarking:

Intel's link to more data on its slides ( http://www.intel.com/performancei=
ndex )

However, this is what I see when I visit that link (and yes, I made a devel=
oper account):

I guess we=E2=80=99ll have to take Intel=E2=80=99s word for it! Anyhow, Gau=
di 3 seems fine; it=E2=80=99s more of an accelerator like a TPU than a more=
 general purpose GPU, but that=E2=80=99s well-suited for LLM workloads in p=
articular. Notably, it is manufactured by TSMC, a legacy of its development=
 by Habana Labs, which Intel acquired in 2019. What was notable to me was t=
he way that Intel CEO Pat Gelsinger framed the entire keynote, which was en=
tirely about AI workloads:

( https://videopress.com/embed/qxRsN4Am?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

I just ask each one of you, which aspect of your life is not becoming more =
digital? Everything. And everything digital runs on semiconductors, which m=
eans the world is increasingly critical on what we do and what Intel does. =
So will your companies, so will your families, so will every aspect. We=E2=
=80=99re just seeing this accelerate as the era of AI is driving this huge =
momentum. We call it AI everywhere, and with that we=E2=80=99re evolving In=
tel in a fundamental way. Intel Foundry, the systems foundry for the AI era=
, and Intel products, the modular platforms for the AI era.

=E2=80=9CModular=E2=80=9D is not a word that has typically been in Intel=E2=
=80=99s vocabulary, at least as far as I can remember; sure, Intel thrived =
by building the leading x86 chips that undergirded the Windows ecosystem, a=
nd later, the Linux cloud ecosystem, but the company=E2=80=99s profitabilit=
y was predicated on integrating design and manufacturing and its own low-le=
vel software libraries. When it comes to AI, though, Intel is not the leade=
r: Nvidia is, with its own integration, this time between chip design and C=
UDA software. It=E2=80=99s no surprise, then, that Intel now has religion i=
n terms of openness and modularity: Gaudi is directly aimed at enterprises =
who want to own their own data and avoid lock-in, using open source softwar=
e stacks. This is how Gelsinger talked about on-prem workloads (the =E2=80=
=9Cedge=E2=80=9D):

( https://videopress.com/embed/1aRxpf4v?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

So the next piece of bringing AI everywhere is edge and enterprise. The edg=
e is this conglomeration of lots of differerent platforms, lots of differen=
t solutions, but the killer app for the next generation of edge is AI. All =
of a sudden video, analytics, taking advantage of these vast quantities of =
data at the edge, and largely wasted today. Intel=E2=80=99s been delivering=
 edge platforms for many decades and now we=E2=80=99re building on those op=
en standard platform investments, enabling you to bring these new analytica=
l processes, data harvesting, to those platforms.

I call it the three laws of the edge. We see this idea of AI edge becoming =
really important, but should the AI happen in the cloud, or at the edge? I =
call it the three laws: the laws of economics, the laws of physics, and the=
 laws of the land:

* Economics: it=E2=80=99s simply too expensive to bring your data back to t=
he cloud. It gives you better cost control. Bandwidth is the most expensive=
 resource that you have, and cloud is the most expensive compute that you h=
ave in the fleet. So the laws of economics: move it to the edge.
* The second is the laws of physics, as I like to say. How many of you have=
 changed the speed of light this week? Whether it=E2=80=99s skill shortage,=
 quality, security, all of those things, what=E2=80=99s the roundtrip requi=
rements? What=E2=80=99s the user interface expectations for instantaneous r=
esponse, or how fast does the robotic arm need a response? If it=E2=80=99s =
20ms you can=E2=80=99t 200ms roundtrip to the cloud. The laws of physics dr=
aw you to the edge. We=E2=80=99re pretty profound technologists, but we ain=
=E2=80=99t changing the speed of light.
* But maybe the third is the most powerful: the laws of the land. We often =
need to keep data on-prem for privacy, regulatory, security reasons, and da=
ta laws have become increasingly diverse and restrictive by regions across =
the world. Every nation has some form of GDPR capabilities and this volume =
of data to tap into at the edge is simply staggering=E2=80=A6

So the three laws. As the edge becomes increasingly important it=E2=80=99s =
going to become, we believe, the dominant AI workload.

This would obviously be good for Intel, for several reasons. First, on prem=
ise data centers remain the strongest part of Intel=E2=80=99s business; hyp=
erscalers will do the work to support a better chip (as they have with AMD=
=E2=80=99s offerings), but it=E2=80=99s often easier and more cost effectiv=
e for smaller fleets to stick with what they are used to. That, by extensio=
n, means that Intel has deep and enduring channel relationships to leverage=
 for AI. Second, while total cost of ownership is a function of performance=
 and price, utilization matters: it=E2=80=99s one thing for a cloud provide=
r to offer an Nvidia solution as a service that could be used by all of its=
 customers, ensuring it=E2=80=99s never sitting idle; an enterprise that bu=
ys their own hardware is the only user, so if it=E2=80=99s not using it all=
 of the time, or unsure of its utilization rate, it=E2=80=99s a potential w=
aste of money to buy the fastest possible solution that costs dramatically =
more. Third =E2=80=94 and related to this point =E2=80=94 Intel=E2=80=99s A=
I story isn=E2=80=99t just about Gaudi, but also about inference on its Xeo=
n chips, which, obviously, can be used for more standard workloads as well.

A big question, of course, is how much better cloud AI will be than whateve=
r Intel can offer on the edge; the primary use case Gelsinger highlighted w=
as Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) using the Llama 2 model, where the =
LLM is basically a user interface to uncover internal data. This is, by all=
 accounts, the use case that is getting traction =E2=80=94 Accenture said i=
n December it had $450 million in generative AI-related bookings ( https://=
www.investopedia.com/accenture-gets-a-boost-from-ai-but-warns-business-spen=
ding-is-slowing-8417944 ) , which I have heard from folks on the ground are=
 mostly for this specific use case =E2=80=94 and open source models on Inte=
l hardware seem like they will be good enough, particularly for data that i=
s stored on-prem. That is a use case where modularity is working, and the o=
ther thing in Intel=E2=80=99s favor is that basically everyone else in the =
industry is pushing for the exact same sort of structure, in an attempt to =
stop giving Nvidia so much money.

Meta MTIA 2
-----------

Again from Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-04-10/m=
eta-debuts-new-ai-chip-aiming-to-decrease-reliance-on-nvidia ) :

Meta Platforms Inc. is deploying a new homegrown chip to help power its art=
ificial intelligence services, aiming to decrease its reliance on semicondu=
ctors from Nvidia Corp. and other outside companies. The chip, announced We=
dnesday, is the latest version of the Meta Training and Inference Accelerat=
or, or MTIA, which helps rank and recommend content across Facebook and Ins=
tagram. Meta released the first MTIA product last year.

Meta=E2=80=99s pivot to AI services has brought increased demand for comput=
ing power. Last year, the social media giant released its own version of an=
 AI model to compete with OpenAI=E2=80=99s ChatGPT. It also added new gener=
ative AI features to its social apps, including customized stickers and cel=
ebrity-faced chatbot characters.

The MTIA family of chips is something Meta has been working on for several =
years, starting well before ChatGPT; these chips are specially tuned for Me=
ta=E2=80=99s specific needs around recommendation algorithms; the company a=
