0c2XDgOgS50IYuk-zIo2uQW0KCHXmYA ) it uses for its more generalized generati=
ve AI efforts. Meta is, needless to say, the exception that proves the rule=
 in terms of the capacity to consume its own chip investments; it=E2=80=99s=
 also another advantage the company has relative to potential competitors i=
n digital advertising. I wrote in Meta Myths ( https://stratechery.com/2022=
/meta-myths/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnB=
hc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9yd=
C5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJo=
dHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIyL21ldGEtbXl0aHMvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MTU3Nzk=
1NTgsImlhdCI6MTcxMzE4NzU1OCwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL2=
9hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvc=
nk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNl=
IjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.LWKXKUe7C_FLC7tC7B3_ROwyI4w12NOm9aVia3rGmK4hb83HJh8UgBhBPNv=
Fzv_Y5hDviZKg2KDJ1Iur9UqB7Q-6ZlEJ24HqfjLf8zaGrrfMc4j-QtvYT5YC5aQQY5lJv5QSn1=
-_a5wM5AXF2DL5VbfBqXTU-DE2R8iURC-UrKKlfBqrEpFTBjtiJj-thDuFhcWfAkGR_98hmE6OQ=
SB8gAChrwALiafe9Lw6qIS-QEh6v4Mtk74ligLuTHiMXQZjsHqOu2h1eIC3loBlz5B-4pMjAehu=
ZJfHXixJehPxo8hongJWoayCZm7PJovVYegFBd4zYVoJqefBbib41LeYCw ) :

Meta has huge data centers, but those data centers are primarily about CPU =
compute, which is what is needed to power Meta=E2=80=99s services. CPU comp=
ute is also what was necessary to drive Meta=E2=80=99s deterministic ad mod=
el, and the algorithms it used to recommend content from your network.

The long-term solution to ATT, though, is to build probabilistic models tha=
t not only figure out who should be targeted (which, to be fair, Meta was a=
lready using machine learning for), but also understanding which ads conver=
ted and which didn=E2=80=99t. These probabilistic models will be built by m=
assive fleets of GPUs, which, in the case of Nvidia=E2=80=99s A100 cards, c=
ost in the five figures; that may have been too pricey in a world where det=
erministic ads worked better anyways, but Meta isn=E2=80=99t in that world =
any longer, and it would be foolish to not invest in better targeting and m=
easurement=E2=80=A6

ATT hurt Meta more than any other company, because it already had by far th=
e largest and most finely-tuned ad business, but in the long run it should =
deepen Meta=E2=80=99s moat. This level of investment simply isn=E2=80=99t v=
iable for a company like Snap or Twitter or any of the other also-rans in d=
igital advertising (even beyond the fact that Snap relies on cloud provider=
s instead of its own data centers); when you combine the fact that Meta=E2=
=80=99s ad targeting will likely start to pull away from the field (outside=
 of Google), with the massive increase in inventory that comes from Reels (=
which reduces prices), it will be a wonder why any advertiser would bother =
going anywhere else.

Digital advertising evolved the way it did in part because CPU compute was =
treated as essentially free; machine learning inference, though, costs more=
, which means infrastructure is a meaningful differentiator. Meta doesn=E2=
=80=99t just have the resources to pay for inference: they also have a stru=
ctural cost advantage (outside of Google) by using their own chips.

Google Axion
------------

Google, meanwhile, has famously been building TPUs for a decade, but is now=
 getting in the CPU game. From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.co=
m/tech/google-expands-in-house-chip-efforts-in-costly-ai-battle-3121c852 ) =
:

Google is making more of its own semiconductors, preparing a new chip that =
can handle everything from YouTube advertising to big data analysis as the =
company tries to combat rising artificial-intelligence costs. The new chip,=
 called Axion, is a type of chip commonly used in big data centers. It adds=
 to Google=E2=80=99s efforts stretching back more than a decade to develop =
new computing resources, beginning with specialized chips used for AI work.=
 Google has leaned into that strategy since the late 2022 release of ChatGP=
T kicked off an arms race that has threatened its dominant position as a ga=
teway to the internet.

This excerpt overstates the case, at least as far as AI is concerned: Axion=
 is an ARM-based CPU, meant for general computing tasks, not AI; the better=
 comparison is AWS=E2=80=99s Graviton line of processors, and the company t=
hat should be concerned is not Nvidia, but Intel (and AMD). Those are the p=
rocessors that are being challenged by Axion. From Google=E2=80=99s blog po=
st ( https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/compute/introducing-googles-new=
-arm-based-cpu ) :

Axion processors combine Google=E2=80=99s silicon expertise with Arm=E2=80=
=99s highest performing CPU cores to deliver instances with up to 30% bette=
r performance than the fastest general-purpose Arm-based instances availabl=
e in the cloud today, up to 50% better performance and up to 60% better ene=
rgy-efficiency than comparable current-generation x86-based instances. That=
=E2=80=99s why we=E2=80=99ve already started deploying Google services like=
 BigTable, Spanner, BigQuery, Blobstore, Pub/Sub, Google Earth Engine, and =
the YouTube Ads platform on current generation Arm-based servers and plan t=
o deploy and scale these services and more on Axion soon.

Built using the Arm Neoverse=E2=84=A2 V2 CPU, Axion processors deliver gian=
t leaps in performance for general-purpose workloads like web and app serve=
rs, containerized microservices, open-source databases, in-memory caches, d=
ata analytics engines, media processing, CPU-based AI training and inferenc=
ing, and more. Axion is underpinned by Titanium, a system of purpose-built =
custom silicon microcontrollers and tiered scale-out offloads. Titanium off=
loads take care of platform operations like networking and security, so Axi=
on processors have more capacity and improved performance for customer work=
loads. Titanium also offloads storage I/O processing to Hyperdisk, our new =
block storage service that decouples performance from instance size and tha=
t can be dynamically provisioned in real time.

All of these claims are based on Google=E2=80=99s internal data, so take th=
em with the commensurate grain of salt, but it=E2=80=99s generally safe to =
assume that these processors are going to be more efficient and lower cost =
than x86 alternatives; what is particularly compelling, though, is Titanium=
. In short, Google is custom-designing these chips to work specifically wit=
h Google=E2=80=99s internal software, to maximize those efficiency and perf=
ormance gains.

This, by extension, gets at one of the fundamental problems facing Intel. M=
odularization is all well-and-good and the appropriate strategy when you ar=
e trying to catch up with an integrated leader; it=E2=80=99s also the fast =
route to commoditization and lower margins. What is even worse, though, is =
when integration happens elsewhere in the value chain in a way that exclude=
s your product entirely. No, not everything in Google=E2=80=99s cloud will =
go to ARM, but the number of ways in which Google can leverage the ability =
to build chips that are designed around its software is only going to incre=
ase. Needless to say, Intel=E2=80=99s foundry efforts =E2=80=94 which will =
give the company the opportunity to at least make the ARM-based chips that =
are moving in on its core workloads =E2=80=94 are essential for the company=
=E2=80=99s long-run future.

